1 Introduction to soils

1.1 Definition

A granular material is a collection of particles such that each particle is in contact with several of its neighbor. Soil is a granular material; variety of minerals form the soil particles, which result from weathering of the rock: physical weathering‚Äìmechanical processes such as temperature fluctuation, abrasion; chemical weathering‚Äìchemical interaction of air and water with fissured rock; biological weathering‚Äìbreakdown because of burrowing animals, plan roots. Fluids‚Äìair, water, or some other fluids‚Äìare present in the pore spaces.

Readings: Principle of rock weathering, Clays and weathering cycles

The soil particle size ranges from 1Œºm\mu{m} to 1mm. We name the soils on the basis of their particle sizes, as it correlates with the soil behavior. Colloidal mixtures have roughly the clay size particles which explain some of the behavior of clays.

1.2.3 Grain size distribution

The soil behavior is a function of grain size distribution; grain size distribution is often present as a probability distribution function (cumulative):

Where XX is the random variable corresponding to soil particle size.

We use coefficient of uniformity (CUC_{U}) and coefficient of curvature (CCC_{C}) to compare the grain size distributions.

CU=D60D10CC=(D30)2D10D60\begin{align} C_{U} = \dfrac{D_{60}}{D_{10}} \\ C_{C} = \dfrac{\left(D_{30}\right)^{2}}{D_{10}D_{60}} \end{align}

Note: The structure and morphology of the soil is independent of the grain size distribution.

1.2.4 Plasticity

Plasticity is the ability of the soil to deform without crumbling when mixed with water. Plasticity is quantified with the Atterberg consistency limit test using plasticity indices‚Äìshrinkage limit (SL), plastic limit (PL), and liquid limit (LL). Plasticity index (PI) is defined as:

PI=LL‚àíPL\begin{align} PI = LL-PL \end{align}

Carbonates are found in residual soils of carbonate rocks (limestone and dolomite). Iron and aluminium oxides are present in the tropical soil. Iron oxide causes reddish color of soil. Sulphate and gypsum occur in arid regions.

1.4 Effective stress principle

We are interested in the hydo-mechanical properties of soils for design problems. The hydraulic properties are related with the transport of fluid in the pore spaces, whereas the mechanical properties are related with the stiffness and strength of the soil (soil skeleton, precisely). The stiffness and strength of soil derive from the interaction of particles:

  1. Elastic deformation at contacts. [elastic]
  2. Bending of elongated particles. [elastic]
  3. Particle crushing at contacts. [inelastic]
  4. Particle breakage. [inelastic]
  5. Particle sliding or rolling. [inelastic]

elastic deformation‚Äìenergy stored (Elastic strains‚Äì10‚àí510^{-5}.) inelastic deformation‚Äìenergy dissipated

The crushing at particle contacts and breakage occur at relatively high pressure. These would not be consider for this discussion. Any inelastic deformation would result from the pore collapse or expansion due to sliding or rolling of particles at the contacts. The contact law and the imposed contact stresses are responsible for deformation at the contacts. To avoid the contact law (unknown), Terzaghi introduced effective stress as a representative of fraction of total stress at the contact. The effective stress principle states

The total force acting on area A of soil is partly supported by the soil skeleton (through contacts between soil particles) and partly by the pore fluid.

We write effective stress principle as Total force=Force on the soil skeleton+Force on the pore fluidTotal stress=Stress on soil skeleton+Pore pressureœÉij=œÉij‚Ä≤+uŒ¥ij\begin{align} \text{Total force} &= \text{Force on the soil skeleton} + \text{Force on the pore fluid}\\ \text{Total stress} &= \text{Stress on soil skeleton} + \text{Pore pressure}\\ \sigma_{ij} &= \sigma_{ij}^{'} + u\delta_{ij} \end{align}

Effective stress is different from the contact stress: it is related with the force on the soil skeleton.

If we apply dœÉijd\sigma_{ij} on a saturated soil with undrained condition (no volume change), pore fluid carries the additional stress but not the soil skeleton. We can show this by the following:

dœÉij=dœÉij‚Ä≤+duŒ¥ijdœÉij‚Ä≤=ùíûijkl‚Ä≤dœµkldu=KfdœµfdœÉij=ùíûijkl‚Ä≤dœµkl+ùí¶fŒ∑fdœµkkŒ¥ijdsij=ùíûijkl‚Ä≤dekldp‚Ä≤=19ùíûjjkk‚Ä≤dœµpp\begin{align} d\sigma_{ij} &= d\sigma_{ij}^{'} + du\delta_{ij} \\ d\sigma_{ij}^{'} &= \mathcal{C}_{ijkl}^{'} d\epsilon_{kl} \\ du &= K_{f}d\epsilon_{f} \\ d\sigma_{ij} &= \mathcal{C}_{ijkl}^{'} d\epsilon_{kl} + \dfrac{\mathcal{K}_{f}}{\eta_{f}} d\epsilon_{kk} \delta_{ij} \\ ds_{ij} &= \mathcal{C}_{ijkl}^{'}de_{kl} \\ dp^{'} &= \dfrac{1}{9}\mathcal{C}_{jjkk}^{'}d\epsilon_{pp} \end{align}

Any additional stress is shared by the pore fluid and the soil skeleton; the pore fluid deformation is equal to the deformation of skeleton pores‚Äìwe use same strain tensor for both pore fluid and skeleton. It is inaccurate to say, ‚Äúthere is no volumetric deformation in undrained condition.‚Äù; however, the volumetric deformation is significantly small. For this significantly small volumetric strain due to increment in stress, the pore fluid pressure changes significantly and trace of the effective stress by a small amount, since:

Note that we can not say much about dsijds_{ij} without more information.

We allow excess pore fluid pressure to dissipate in drained condition. An accurate drained condition requires:

td‚â™tli\begin{align} t_{d} \ll t_{li} \end{align}

Where tdt_{d} is time require for dissipation (we can assume 90% degree of consolidation); tlit_{li} is time require for load increment by a significant amount.

We cannot achieve a perfect drained condition since 100% consolidation is never achieved, and even to keep a high degree of consolidation the rate of loading has to be very small. In experiments, we always see significant excess pore fluid pressure in drained condition.

Further, we assume the saturated conditions which are partially assumed.

1.4.1 Continuum modeling of soils

What do we mean by shear strength of the soil? Is it shear strength of 1 particle, 10 particles, 1000 particles, 1 billion particles? It is found that there should be sufficient number of particles (around 10 particles) to have a consistent soil property. If we have lesser number of particles, it will constitute a highly discontinuous field of that particular field. With lesser number of particles we can not use the continuum theories and models.

2 Geology and the genesis of soils and rocks

Geology is very important in understanding of the soils; behavior of soil is a function of it‚Äôs structure. The natural soil deposits have different structures depending on their origin.

Earth is a giant recycling machine, constantly transforming soil into rock, solid rock into molten rock, molten rock into rock again, and rock into soil. Additionally material gets transported from one place to other (figure~).

2.1 Rock genesis

2.1.1 Igneous rock

At the convergent boundaries, two tectonic plates collide and generate heat; high temperature and pressure magnifies the heat at greater depths. This excess heat melts rock into magma, migrates it upward, and creates volcano. Magma cools very fast on the surface, solidifies and generates magmatic rocks, called extrusive igneous rocks. In some cases, the magma does not reach the surface, and solidifies slowly within a cooler rock mass, called intrusive igneous rocks.

The cooling rate controls the appearance and properties of the rock. Large grains of minerals form due to grouping during hardening with slow cooling in intrusive rocks; we can identify mica, feldspar, and quartz in graphite. Minerals group together; bonds between same substances have lower potential energy. Minerals grouping slows down if the cooling is too fast; it gives a homogeneous appearance to extrusive rocks, such as basalt.

2.1.2 Sedimentary rock

Sedimentary rocks form due to compression and cementation between soil particles at larger depths. The pore water flows through these soils and deposits the cement at the particle contacts and voids. The soil goes through various forms in this process called diagenesis or lithification. Sedimentary rocks are named after the base particulate material.

Table 3: Particle base and sedimentary rocks
Base Sedimentary rock
Sands Sandstones
Clays Claystones
Silts Siltstones
Clays and silts Shales
Gravels Conglomerate or breccias

2.1.3 Metamorphic rock

Metamorphic rock forms when igneous, sedimentary, or other metamorphic rocks transform under great temperature and pressure. The high temperatures cause flow of rocks and with high pressure the mineral realign themselves along the direction of the pressure.

Table 4: Metamorphic rock source
Parent rock Metamorphic rock
Granite Gneiss
Sandstone Quartzite
Shale Slate
Shale Schist
Limestones Marble

2.2 Soil genesis

2.2.1 residual soils

Rock weathers into minerals or mineral aggregates‚Äìsoils‚Äìdue to physical and chemical processes. These minerals affect the behavior of residual soils. Quartz is the most common mineral in soil. Weathering increases from surface to bedrock; sand is most abundant near the bedrock and clays occur near the surface.

2.2.2 Transported soils

The residual soil erode and transport to other places by various agent to create soil deposits. The transported soils have different grain size distribution and fabric depending on the deposition process and transporting agent. We have the following as the transporting agents and corresponding soil.

Table 5: Transported soils
Transporting agent Soil name Observations
Wind Aeolian Uniform particle sizes
Water (streams and rivers) Alluvial Intermixed clay, silt, and sand layers
Water (lakes) Lacustrine layering due to seasonal factors
Water (ocean) Marine Possibly quick clay
Ice (glacier advance) Glacial soils Wide range of particle sizes
Gravity*(rolling on cliff) Colluvial Wide range of particle sizes
  • Aeolian deposits‚ÄìWind carries the soil particles of same size due to its carrying capacity; dune sand for example is quite uniform in gradation.
  • Alluvial deposits‚ÄìRiver stream carries particles of various sizes with it, deposits the particles depending on the velocity of stream which changes depended on the basin profile.

3 Classic soils

Classic soils are clays and sands‚Äìresidual soils; we have studied them extensively. Gravel and non-plastic silts‚Äìsands plastic silts‚Äìclays

3.1 Silica sand

Silica sand, mostly quartz particles, is found abundantly in the nature. It can be:

  • fine sand
  • medium coarse sand
  • coarse sand

with shapes:

  • Angular
  • Sub-angular
  • Sub-rounded
  • Rounded

Angular particles mobilize higher strength due to the interlocking in comparison to the rounded particles.

3.2 Clays

Composition of clays clays are made up of clay mineral particles. These minerals form with the chemical weathering of rocks (feldspar, mica, and ferro-magnesian). Clays are the end product of weathering since they are resistant to weather. Clay minerals behave plastically in the presence of water due to net negative charge. Basic components of minerals:

  • Silicon tetrahedron
  • Aluminium or magnesian octahedron

In these, central cation (Si+4Si^{+4}, Al+3Al^{+3}, or Mg+2Mg^{+2}) is surrounded by the oxygens or hydroxyls. These components form silica sheet with silica cation, alumina sheet (gibbsite sheet) with aluminium ion (Al+3Al^{+3}), and brucite sheet with magnesium ions (Mg+2Mg^{+2}). The combination of these sheets form different clay minerals.

Table 6: Common clay minerals
Clay minerals Structure Interlayer bonding Particle dimensions Swelling
Montmorillonite 2:1 (gibbsite) Water + cations < 2Œº\mu t-10A Yes
Saponite 2:1 (brucit) Van der Waals < 2Œº\mu t-10A Yes
Illite 2:1 (gibbsite) Potassium < 4Œº\mu t-30A No
Kaolinite 1:1 (gibbsite) Hydrogen bonds < 4Œº\mu t-2E04A No

t is the thickness of the mineral. Thicker bonds prevent water entry into layers.

Montmorillonite, bentonite and saponite come under smectites.

Kaolinite - granite Smectite - basalt

Strong bonds suppress swelling behavior. Weak bonds promotes swelling behavior.

3.3 Clay-water systems

Double layer: Several layers of sheets (brucite, gibbsite, and silica sheets) for a clay particles. The interlayer forces are weaker than the forces forming a sheet that results in platy particles. We can think of clays as plates with net negative charge on the surface due to which clays have significant water content. The cations of electrolytes (dissolved in water) get attracted to the clay particle surface, and concentration of cations increases towards the particle surface. Clay particles form a layer of structured water near its surface: double layer system. Clay particles with double layer, enlarged clay particle, repel each other. The enlarged clay particles have an extent of:

1K=œµŒ∫BT2n0e2ŒΩ2\begin{align} \dfrac{1}{K} = \sqrt{\dfrac{\epsilon\kappa_{B}T}{2n_{0}e^{2}\nu^{2}}} \end{align}

Where, œµ\epsilon - permittivity of medium, Œ∫B\kappa_{B} - Boltzmann constant, TT - absolute temperature, n0n_{0} - electrolyte concentration, ŒΩ\nu - valency of the cation, ee - electronic charge.

1K\dfrac{1}{K} increases with the cation sizes; in the above formula, cations are point objects‚Äìdimensionless.

Sedimentation of clay in water: Clay particles in alluvial or aeolian deposits get unloaded in lake, ocean, or desert. They form different fabric:

  1. Grouping of particles
  • Aggregated - particles are grouped by face to face connections; strong attractive forces act at close distance between two particles.
  • Dispersed - particles are not grouped via face to face connections.
  1. Connections between clay particle or particle groups
  • Flocculated (edge to face or edge to edge deposition)
  • Deflocculated - No connection between particle or particle groups

Aggregation and flocculation are independent processes.

4 Non-classic soils

Carbonate sands, exist in tropical and subtropical regions, consist residue of shells and skeletons of marine organism as particles‚Äìmade up of calcium carbonates. Carbonate sand particles are angular and hollow, and show excessive crushing on shearing. Interlocking because of angularity causes high friction angle.

Marine clays, form in salt water conditions with high electrolyte concentration, have small double-layer and flocculated fabric. Quick clays form after fresh water replaces salt-water; salt-water leaches out of the marine clays.

Expansive soils contain large amount of smectites, and swell in contact of water. The inter-particle electrolyte concentration decreases with dilution and double layer thickness increases. The double layer expansion causes swelling in expansive soils. The swelling in these soils is non-uniform and causes cracks in the superstructures.

Loess is an aeolian deposit of silt in the presence of smectites, which acts as binder.

Organic soils, e.g.¬†peats, form due to decomposition of plants and roots, and are very soft, weak, compressible soils. These soils also so secondary compression.

We observe a mix of these soils in natural soil deposits. The fines act in two ways in between coarse particles: reduces the permittivity, interferes in the interaction of larger particles; the combination results in two types of fabric:

  1. Non-floating fabric - Fines only occupy the voids; small fine content.
  2. Floating fabric - Coarse particles floats in matrix of fines, i.e., fine particles link the coarse particles.

We can weigh the soil easily.

Atterberg limits Fine soil behaves plastically upon mixing with water and flows like a viscous fluid beyond a limit, i.e., we can mold them into different shapes without any distortion.

Shrinkage limit:

Plastic limit: The minimum water content for which soil behaves plastically is the plastic limit. If we lower the water content, we would not be able to mold it in different shapes. We roll the soil into 3mm3mm threads, the water content for which threads crumbles upon rolling is the plastic limit.

Liquid limit: Fine soils behaves like a viscous fluids on mixing with water at liquid limit. We pour the soil paste in a dish and make a grove (triangular in shape). We drop the dish from 10mm10mm height and count the number of blows to close the groove. The water content corresponding to a sample for which groove closes on 25th drop is the liquid limit.
